{| class="wikitable" |---- !Name of the convict !Sentenced date !Commuted date !Charge !Jurisdiction !Description !Image |---- |[[Francisco Guerrero (killer)|Francisco Guerrero Pérez]] |1888 |1904 |Murder, rape and attempt murder |{{flag|Distrito Federal (Mexico)|1880}} |[[Serial killer]] who was sentenced to death penalty for one murder and another attempt, he was 48 years-old and was suspected of 20 murders more. His sentence was commuted by only 20 years-prison for Presidential order ([[Porfirio Díaz]], the Mexican President in this time, had an anti-death penalty posture). Mistakly he recibed an indulted in 1904. In 1908, Guerrero killed again, his victim an old lady who was raped and beheaded. Guerrero was sentenced to death again, but he died of a cerebral tromboembolism in 1910 before to be executed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://culturacolectiva.com/history/the-chalequero-mexican-serial-killer/ |title=The 'Mexican Ripper' Who Murdered At Least A Dozen Prostitutes In The 19th Century |last=Romero |first=Carolina |date=24 April 2017 |website=Cultura Colectiva.com |publisher=Cultura Colectiva |access-date=23 October 2017 |quote= He was caught in a tavern in 1888 and sentenced to death. However, then-president Porfirio Díaz, lowered his sentence to only 20 years of imprisonment at the Fortress of San Juan de Ulúa, a prison set on an island. However, the "Mexican Ripper" was set in 1904 because his file was misplaced into the pile of political prisoners who were granted forgiveness. Four years later, in 1908, the body of an old woman, who people assured was connected to prostitution, was found in the same river, presenting the same marks and cause of death as Guerrero's previous victims. He was arrested and sent to the Lecumberri prison in the city, where he was sentenced to death. However, he soon died due to a hemiparesis caused by a brain congestion. He passed away in a hospital bed when he was 70 years old, avoiding the rope once again.}}</ref> |[[File:Francisco Guerrero (002).jpg|150px]] |---- |Eusebio Yocupicio Soto |1950 |? |Murder |{{flag|Sonora}} ||[[Mayo people|Yoreme]] Amerindian man who was sentenced to death penalty, together to other three Yoreme men, accused of 7 serial murders committed in [[Huatabampo]], [[Sonora]], during 1950. According with the policial investigations, Yocupicio and the others men maintained homosexual relationships, this rumor released around to the community, and the men were stigmatized, they planificaed their revenge, murdered and mutilated to seven men who they guiltied for the homosexuality rumor. Yocupicio and his accomplices was sentenced to death but their condemn were commuted to 30 years-prison before to apeleter. Several [[extenuating circumstances]] were considered as the socio-culthural conditions and the antecedent discrimination.<ref>{{cite news |last=Buitimea Yocupicio |first=Emilia |title=Los huipas: los míticos asesinos seriales de Sonora|trans-title=Los Huipas: the mythical serial killers from Sonora |url=https://www.vice.com/es_mx/article/kwvp83/crimen-y-confesion-de-los-huipas-0000682-v8n9 |language=Spanish |work=VICE |access-date=23 October 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Arroyo Cano|first=Alejandro |title=La historia de los asesinos seriales de Sonora |trans-title=The history of serial killers from Sonora |url=https://culturacolectiva.com/historia/la-historia-de-los-asesinos-seriales-de-sonora/ |language=Spanish |work=Cultura Colectiva |access-date=23 October 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Mungarro Daniels |first=Alejandro|title=Tesopaco: el último fusilamiento en Sonora|trans-title=Tesopaco: the last shooted in Sonora |url= http://www.infocajeme.com/opinion/2016/07/el-ultimo-fusilamiento-en-sonora/|language=Spanish |work=Info Cajeme|access-date=23 October 2017 |quote=La historia oficial data que la última pena de muerte aplicada en sonora y en México fue en Hermosillo, aplicándose esta pena a José Rosario Don Juan Zamarripa y Francisco Ruiz Corrales, siendo al Lic. Roberto Reynoso Dávila ,Juez, quien dicto aquella sentencia, dictada primeramente en 1950 para José Rosario Don Juan Zamarripa y en 1955 para Francisco Ruiz Corrales ,valorando los delitos que estas personas habían cometido, determinando que esa era la pena que les correspondía, aplicando esta el día 17 de Junio de 1957, en horas de la madrugada. Al aplicarse la penas de muerte a estas personas había también otros reos que esperaban en prisión la aplicación de la misma, entre ellos, cuatro indígenas mayos que con sus crímenes conmocionaron a la sociedad sonorense de aquel tiempo ellos eran, Adelaido Huipas Quijano, Leonardo Yocupicio Huipas, Eusebio Yocupicio Soto y Basilio Humo Valenzuela, sin embargo a ellos pese a que el juez de Primera Instancia los condeno a muerte, apelaron la sentencia, posteriormente se les cambio por pena de cárcel por 30 años, debiéndola cumplir en la capital del estado. Eusebio Yocupicio Soto y Basilio Humo Valenzuela murieron en la prisión en Hermosillo Sonora, los otros dos estuvieron presos treinta años. }}</ref> | |---- |Basilio Humo Valenzuela |1950 |? |Murder |{{flag|Sonora}} |Yoreme Amerindian man condemned to death together to Eusebio Yocupicio. | |---- |Leonardo Yocupicio Huipas |1950 |? |Murder |{{flag|Sonora}} |Yoreme Amerindian man condemned to death together to Eusebio Yocupicio. | |---- |Adelaido Huipas Quijano |1950 |? |Murder |{{flag|Sonora}} |Yoreme Amerindian man condemned to death together to Eusebio Yocupicio. | |---- |Dykes Askew Simmons |March 1961 |1969 |Murder |{{flag|Nuevo León}} |American [[rampage killer]] who was sentenced to death penalty for triple homicide. In 1959, he massacred three men, Villagómez Pérez family members. Simmons was a known mental patient, for this reason his sentence was commuted to 30 years-prison.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bacchi |first=Umberto |date=31 July 2013 |title=Real Hannibal Lecter was Murderous Gay Mexican Doctor Alfredo Ballí Treviño |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/hannibal-lecter-gay-mexican-doctor-alfredo-ball-495908 |work=International Business Times |location=Nuevo León, Mexico |access-date=21 October 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Rodríguez |first=Christian |title=Hannibal Lecter: una historia real basada en un mexicano |trans-title=Hannibal Lecter: a real store based in a Mexican |url=http://www.esquirelat.com/mundo-esquire/17/01/30/hannibal-lecter-una-historia-real-basada-en-un-mexicano/ |language=Spanish |work=Esquire Latinoamérica |access-date=21 October 2017 }}</ref> | |---- |Dr. Alfredo Ballí Treviño |November 1961 |1981 |Murder |{{flag|Nuevo León}} |33 years-old male physician who was condemned to death penalty for murder and dismember of his boyfriend, Jesús Castillo Rangel. He was the last man condemned to death in Mexico. In October 1959, Dr. Treviño murder his boyfriend after to dispute, drugged him and cut his throat with a scalpel, dismembered body after bleed him. Collocated the parts in a box, and sepulted it in a local relatives´ farm with pretext of it was a medical waste. After to be captured was incarcerated in Topo Chico prison by to wait his execution, but his condem was commuted for 30 years-prison after to death penalty was abolished in Nuevo León. Was a model prisoner and was free after to 20 years, even obtained again his medical licence, died of natural cause in 2009 at the age of 80 years. His history inspired the fictional character [[Hannibal Lecter]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Bacchi |first=Umberto |date=31 July 2013 |title=Real Hannibal Lecter was Murderous Gay Mexican Doctor Alfredo Ballí Treviño |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/hannibal-lecter-gay-mexican-doctor-alfredo-ball-495908 |work=International Business Times |location=Nuevo León, Mexico |access-date=21 October 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Rodríguez |first=Christian |title=Hannibal Lecter: una historia real basada en un mexicano |trans-title=Hannibal Lecter: a real store based in a Mexican |url=http://www.esquirelat.com/mundo-esquire/